AGI - A former Greens Congressman climbed on the balcony above the main entrance of Palazzo Montecitorio> and exhibited two flags of Palestine.» "Based with the massacre in Gaza," he shouted from the balcony where he arrived passing through a side window in balance on the cornice. &nbsp;
<div </div
With the fist closed up, the man, initially unidentified, asked several times to stop the "genocide" in the Gaza Strip > and proceed to the liberation of Israeli hostages. After about ten minutes, the security of the palace and the activist intervened - who wore the jacket, dress code mandatory for having access to the Chamber - was pushed away and the flags were removed. It was then known that the author of the gesture was a former member of the Greens, Stefano Apuzzo. >È&nbsp; he himself reports it while waiting to know what the measures will be taken. Apuzzo entered the palace by virtue of his post > of former MP, with the pretext of visiting the exhibition set up in one of the halls (Apuzzo, among other things, is also art critic)> and came out on the cornice of Montecitorio from a window of the Aldo Moro room.
&nbsp;
The former MP, elected in 1992, thus reached the balcony and exposed the flags to demand the immediate cease-fire in Gaza. "No one stopped me. I exposed two flags of Palestine to the balcony. I asked to stop the massacre, free the Israeli hostages in the hands of Hamas and free the two and a half million Palestinians imprisoned in the Gaza Strip from Israel," explains AGI.
